  <page>
    <title>Amalaric</title>
    <id>1373</id>
    <revision>
      <id>429906171</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-19T16:44:26Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Chris the speller</username>
        <id>525927</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>[[WP:AWB/T|Typo fixing]], replaced: lead by → led by using [[Project:AWB|AWB]] (7660)</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{other uses|Amalric}}
[[File:Amalarico-rey-visigodo.png|thumb|Illustration of '''Amalaric''']]

'''Amalaric''', or in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], ''Amalarico'', (502&lt;ref name=&quot;Brockhaus&quot;&gt;Brockhaus Geschichte Second Edition&lt;/ref&gt; &amp;ndash; 531) was a son of king [[Alaric II]] and of Theodegotho, daughter of [[Theodoric the Great]] and his first wife. Amalaric was himself king of the [[Visigoths]] from 526 till he was assassinated in 531.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

He was a child when his father fell in battle against [[Clovis I]], king of the [[Franks]], in 507. [[Gesalec]] was chosen king and the child Amalaric was carried for safety into [[Hispania]]. After Gesalec was killed in 511, the country and [[Provence]] was thenceforth ruled by Amalaric's maternal grandfather, [[Theodoric the Great|Theodoric]] the Ostrogoth, acting through his vice regent, [[Theudis]], an Ostrogothic nobleman. In 522 the young Amalaric was proclaimed king, and four years later, on Theodoric's death, he assumed full royal power in Hispania and that part of [[Languedoc]] called [[Septimania]], relinquishing [[Provence]] to his cousin [[Athalaric]]. He married [[Clotilde (died 531)|Chrotilda]], daughter of [[Clovis I]]; but his disputes with her over religion, he being an [[Arianism|Arian]] and she a [[Catholicism|Catholic]], brought on him the penalty of a Frankish invasion.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

The invasion was led by [[Childebert I]], king of [[Paris]] (who was also his brother in law, being Clotide's brother). Amalaric was defeated at [[Narbonne]] in 531 and retreated behind the walls of [[Barcelona]], where he was assassinated by his own troops.&lt;ref name=&quot;Brockhaus&quot;/&gt;

