'''AOL Inc.''' ({{nyse|AOL}}, stylized as &quot;'''Aol.'''&quot;, and previously known as '''America Online''') is an [[United States|American]] global [[Internet]] services and media [[company]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web  |url=http://corp.aol.com/press-releases/2009/10/aol-chief-technology-officer-ted-cahall-appointed-new-virginia-technology-boa  |title=AOL Chief Technology Officer Ted Cahall Appointed to New Virginia Technology Board}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news  |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/17/AR2007091700415.html  |title=AOL Moving Executives, Headquarters To New York | work=The Washington Post | first1=Zachary A. |last1=Goldfarb |first2=Sam |last2=Diaz |date=September 18, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; AOL is headquartered at 770 Broadway in New York.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web  |url=http://corp.aol.com/about-aol/company-overview  |title=Company Overview  |publisher=aol.com  |accessdate=May 7, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;GoldfarbHQMove&quot;&gt;{{cite news  |author=Goldfarb, Zachary and Sam Diaz |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/17/AR2007091700415.html  |publisher=[[The Washington Post]] |title= AOL Moving Executives, Headquarters to New York  |date=Tuesday September 18, 2007  |accessdate=May 7, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Founded in 1983 as Control Video Corporation, it has [[franchising|franchised]] its services to companies in several nations around the world or set up [[international]] [[version number|versions]] of its services.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web  |url=http://about.aol.com/international_services  |title=International Services - About AOL}}&lt;/ref&gt;

AOL is best known for its [[online]] [[software suite]], also called ''AOL'', that allowed customers to access the world's largest &quot;[[Walled garden (technology)|walled garden]]&quot; [[online community]] and eventually reach out to the Internet as a whole. At its prime, AOL's membership was over 30 million members worldwide,&lt;ref name=&quot;lessbemore&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/jul2006/tc20060731_168094.htm |title=Will Less Be More for AOL? |first=Catherine |last=Holahan |publisher=[[BusinessWeek]] |date=2006-07-31 |accessdate=2006-08-01 }}&lt;/ref&gt; most of whom accessed the AOL service through the AOL software suite.

On May 28, 2009, [[Time Warner]] announced that it would [[Corporate spin-off|spin off]] AOL into a separate public company. The spinoff occurred on December 9, 2009,&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2009/11/16/technology/tech-us-aol.html ''Time Warner to Spin Off AOL on December 9'']&quot;  Retrieved on November 16, 2009.&lt;/ref&gt; ending the eight year relationship between the two companies.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://money.usnews.com/money/business-economy/technology/articles/2009/05/28/time-warner-to-spin-off-aol-ending-ill-fated-deal.html ''Time Warner to spin off AOL, ending ill-fated deal''].&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;
{{TOC limit|limit=2}}

== Description ==
[[File:America Online logo.svg|thumb|left|150px|Original logo for America Online, 1991–2006]]
With regional branches around the world, the former American &quot;[[goliath]] among [[Internet service provider]]s&quot;&lt;ref name=&quot;lessbemore&quot; /&gt; once had more than 30 million subscribers&lt;ref name=&quot;lessbemore&quot; /&gt; on several continents.  It ranked fourth (behind the Web itself, e-mail, and graphic user interfaces) in a 2007 USA TODAY retrospective on the 25 events that shaped the first 25 years of the Internet&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://www.usatoday.com/tech/top25-internet.htm | work=USA Today | title=How the Internet took over | date=April 30, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; and was named to the &quot;.com 25&quot; by a panel of Silicon Valley influencers on the occasion of the same anniversary.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |url = http://www.25yearsof.com/thedotcom25/ | title=The .com25 Honorees |publisher=thedotcom25 | accessdate=19 October 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In January 2000, AOL and [[Time Warner]] announced plans to merge. The terms of the deal called for AOL shareholders to own 55% of the new, combined company. The deal closed on January 11, 2001 after receiving regulatory approval from the [[Federal Trade Commission|FTC]], the [[Federal Communications Commission|FCC]], and the [[European Union]].

'''AOL Time Warner, Inc.''', as the company was then called, was led by executives from AOL, SBI, and Time Warner. [[Gerald Levin]], who had served as [[CEO]] of Time Warner, was CEO of the new company. [[Steve Case]] served as [[Board of Directors|Chairman]], J. Michael Kelly (from AOL) was the [[Chief Financial Officer]], [[Robert W. Pittman]] (from AOL) and [[Dick Parsons]] (from Time Warner) served as Co-[[Chief Operating Officer]]s. The total value of AOL stock subsequently went from $226 billion to about $20 billion.&lt;ref name=&quot;scrapcharge&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20060727/wr_nm/media_timewarner_aol_dc_7 |title=AOL expected to scrap charges |first=Kenneth |last=Li |publisher=[[Yahoo!]] |date=2006-07-26 |accessdate=2006-08-09 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060818100420/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20060727/wr_nm/media_timewarner_aol_dc_7 &lt;!-- Bot retrieved archive --&gt; |archivedate = 2006-08-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; Similarly, its customer base decreased to 10.1 million subscribers as of November 2007,&lt;ref name=&quot;custBase&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.computerworld.com/action/article.do?command=viewArticleBasic&amp;articleId=9046103&amp;intsrc=news_ts_head |title=AOL revenue, subscribers plummet |first=Linda |last=Rosencrance |publisher=ComputerWorld |date=2007-11-08 |accessdate=2007-11-12 }}&lt;/ref&gt; just narrowly ahead of [[Comcast]] and [[AT&amp;T Yahoo!]]. As of June 2010, AOL's subscriber base dropped to 4.4 million.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url = http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1468516/000119312510176095/d10q.htm | title=Form 10-Q | publisher=[[United States Securities and Exchange Commission]] |accessdate=19 October 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:AOL old logo.svg|thumb|150px|left|The second logo for AOL, used from 2006–2009]]
News reports in late 2005 identified companies such as [[Yahoo!]], [[Microsoft]], and [[Google]] as candidates for turning AOL into a joint venture;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
|url = http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/nov2005/tc20051111_725373.htm
|title = Has AOL Met Its Match?
|first = Catherine
|last = Yang
|publisher = [[BusinessWeek]]
|date= 2005-11-11
|accessdate = 2006-08-01 }}&lt;/ref&gt; those plans were apparently abandoned when it was revealed on December 20, 2005 that Google would purchase a 5% share of AOL for $1 billion.

AOL was rated both one of the best and worst Internet suppliers in the UK, according to a poll by [[Watchdog (TV series)|BBC Watchdog]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/consumer/tv_and_radio/watchdog/reports/internet/internet_20070321.shtml
|title=''Broadband survey results''
|publisher = [[BBC News]]
|date=2007-03-21
|accessdate = 2007-12-04 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

On March 31, 1997, the short-lived [[eWorld]] was purchased by AOL. The [[Internet service provider|ISP]] side of AOL UK was bought by [[The Carphone Warehouse]] in October 2006 to take advantage of their 100,000 [[Local loop unbundling|LLU]] customers which made The Carphone Warehouse the biggest LLU provider in the UK.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6039740.stm | work=BBC News | title=Carphone Warehouse buying AOL UK | date=October 11, 2006 | accessdate=April 25, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

On May 28, 2009,&lt;ref&gt;[http://topupguru.com/2009/05/28/time-warner-to-spinoff-aol/ Topupguru.com]&lt;/ref&gt; [[Time Warner]] announced that it would spin AOL off as an independent company once [[Google]]'s shares ceased at the end of the fiscal year, and AOL's page and logo changed afterward.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/30979493/ MSN.com]&lt;/ref&gt;

AOL ceased to be a part of [[Time Warner]] on December 9, 2009. The company declared an [[IPO]] on that day, under the stock symbol NYSE:AOL.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.betanews.com/joewilcox/article/AOLs-decision-to-rebrand-as-Aol-takes-a-bad-brand-and-makes-it-worse/1259015785 BetaNews.com]&lt;/ref&gt;

